1
00:00:42,250 --> 00:00:52,250
subtitled by
assasinX

2
00:01:24,500 --> 00:01:25,515
Grandpa!

3
00:01:25,588 --> 00:01:29,417
You're not supposed to be up here,
looking at that.

4
00:01:29,940 --> 00:01:31,947
I just wanted to know.

5
00:01:33,140 --> 00:01:35,442
Well, you're old enough, I suppose.

6
00:01:36,308 --> 00:01:38,959
You should know the story.

7
00:01:40,533 --> 00:01:42,704
OK, here we go.

8
00:01:43,669 --> 00:01:46,604
It was 1832.

9
00:01:47,637 --> 00:01:50,736
On a night much like this.

10
00:01:55,477 --> 00:01:56,460
Yah!

11
00:01:57,366 --> 00:02:03,411
<i>Charles Carroll was the last surviving
signer of the Declaration of Independence.</i>

12
00:02:04,150 --> 00:02:07,728
<i>He was also a member
of a secret society known as the Masons.</i>

13
00:02:08,310 --> 00:02:11,125
<i>And he knew he was dying.</i>

14
00:02:11,862 --> 00:02:14,252
<i>He woke up his stable boy
in the middle of the night</i>

15
00:02:14,326 --> 00:02:18,833
<i>and ordered him to take him to
the White House to see Andrew Jackson.</i>

16
00:02:18,902 --> 00:02:21,902
<i>Because it was urgent
that he speak to the president.</i>

17
00:02:22,871 --> 00:02:24,365
Did he talk to him?

18
00:02:24,727 --> 00:02:27,542
No. He never got the chance.

19
00:02:27,607 --> 00:02:29,909
<i>The president wasn't there that night.</i>

20
00:02:31,319 --> 00:02:34,353
But Charles Carroll had a secret.

21
00:02:34,423 --> 00:02:38,482
So he took into his confidence
the one person he could,

22
00:02:38,551 --> 00:02:41,398
my grandfather's grandfather,

23
00:02:42,135 --> 00:02:43,924
<i>Thomas Gates.</i>

24
00:02:43,992 --> 00:02:46,097
What was the secret?

25
00:02:48,792 --> 00:02:49,741
A treasure.

26
00:02:51,800 --> 00:02:54,800
A treasure beyond all imagining.

27
00:02:58,712 --> 00:03:01,745
<i>A treasure that had been
fought over for centuries</i>

28
00:03:01,816 --> 00:03:06,039
<i>by tyrants. Pharaohs.
Emperors. Warlords.</i>

29
00:03:06,329 --> 00:03:09,678
<i>And every time it changed hands
it grew larger.</i>

30
00:03:12,537 --> 00:03:14,992
And then suddenly...

31
00:03:15,321 --> 00:03:17,329
it vanished.

32
00:03:19,066 --> 00:03:22,132
<i>It didn't reappear
for more than a thousand years.</i>

33
00:03:22,202 --> 00:03:23,958
<i>When knights from the First Crusade</i>

34
00:03:24,025 --> 00:03:27,320
<i>discovered secret vaults
beneath the Temple of Solomon.</i>

35
00:03:27,386 --> 00:03:29,807
<i>You see. The knights who found the vaults</i>

36
00:03:29,882 --> 00:03:34,138
<i>believed that the treasure
was too great for any one man -</i>

37
00:03:34,202 --> 00:03:36,111
<i>not even a king.</i>

38
00:03:36,186 --> 00:03:42,231
<i>They brought the treasure back to Europe
and took the name "the Knights Templar."</i>

39
00:03:44,635 --> 00:03:47,570
<i>Over the next century
they smuggled it out of Europe</i>

40
00:03:47,642 --> 00:03:50,457
<i>and they formed a new brotherhood
called the Freemasons.</i>

41
00:03:50,523 --> 00:03:53,206
<i>In honor of
the builders of the great temple.</i>

42
00:03:54,523 --> 00:03:55,952
<i>War followed.</i>

43
00:03:56,027 --> 00:03:59,824
<i>By the time of the American Revolution
the treasure had been hidden again.</i>

44
00:03:59,899 --> 00:04:01,971
<i>By then the Masons included</i>

45
00:04:02,043 --> 00:04:06,004
<i>George Washington.
Benjamin Franklin. Paul Revere.</i>

46
00:04:07,003 --> 00:04:08,727
<i>They knew they had to make sure</i>

47
00:04:08,795 --> 00:04:12,090
<i>the treasure would never fall
into the hands of the British.</i>

48
00:04:12,156 --> 00:04:16,117
So they devised a series of clues
and maps to its location.

49
00:04:16,188 --> 00:04:18,905
Over time the clues were lost or forgotten,

50
00:04:18,972 --> 00:04:21,077
until only one remained -

51
00:04:21,148 --> 00:04:26,899
and that was the secret that Charles Carroll
entrusted to young Thomas Gates.

52
00:04:32,733 --> 00:04:33,715
Charlotte.

53
00:04:34,557 --> 00:04:37,873
"The secret lies with Charlotte."

54
00:04:38,525 --> 00:04:40,248
Who's Charlotte?

55
00:04:40,317 --> 00:04:43,863
Oh... not even Mr. Carroll knew that.

56
00:04:43,933 --> 00:04:45,689
Now look here, Ben.

57
00:04:45,757 --> 00:04:50,013
The Freemasons
among our Founding Fathers left us clues.

58
00:04:50,077 --> 00:04:51,506
Like these.

59
00:04:51,582 --> 00:04:54,713
The unfinished pyramid.
The all-seeing eye.

60
00:04:55,229 --> 00:04:59,288
Symbols of the Knights Templar,
guardians of the treasure.

61
00:05:00,029 --> 00:05:04,918
- They're speaking to us through these.
- You mean laughing at us.

62
00:05:04,990 --> 00:05:07,707
You know what that dollar represents?

63
00:05:07,774 --> 00:05:10,262
The entire Gates family fortune.

64
00:05:10,335 --> 00:05:14,558
Six generations of fools...
chasing after fool's gold.

65
00:05:14,623 --> 00:05:17,918
It's not about the money,
Patrick. It's never been about the money.

66
00:05:17,982 --> 00:05:20,055
Come on, son. Time to go.

67
00:05:20,671 --> 00:05:23,322
You can... say your goodbyes.

68
00:05:30,496 --> 00:05:32,056
Grandpa?

69
00:05:32,127 --> 00:05:33,720
Hm?

70
00:05:35,103 --> 00:05:37,242
Are we knights?

71
00:05:39,647 --> 00:05:41,982
Do you want to be?

72
00:05:42,048 --> 00:05:45,364
All right. Um... kneel.

73
00:05:56,544 --> 00:05:58,367
Benjamin Franklin Gates,

74
00:05:58,433 --> 00:06:03,801
you take upon yourself the duty
of the Templars, the Freemasons

75
00:06:03,873 --> 00:06:06,688
and the family Gates.

76
00:06:07,425 --> 00:06:09,367
Do you so swear?

77
00:06:09,441 --> 00:06:11,351
I so swear.

78
00:06:33,058 --> 00:06:35,327
I was thinking about
Henson and Peary,

79
00:06:35,394 --> 00:06:39,802
crossing this kind of terrain with nothing
more than dog sleds and on foot.

80
00:06:39,874 --> 00:06:42,394
- Can you imagine?
- It's extraordinary.

81
00:06:48,227 --> 00:06:50,136
We getting closer?

82
00:06:50,211 --> 00:06:54,040
Assuming Ben's theory's correct
and my tracking model's accurate,

83
00:06:54,115 --> 00:06:56,734
<i>we should be getting very close.</i>

84
00:06:56,803 --> 00:07:00,283
But don't go by me -
I broke a shoelace this morning.

85
00:07:03,395 --> 00:07:06,941
- It's... it's a bad omen.
- Shall we turn around and go home?

86
00:07:07,011 --> 00:07:10,011
Or we could pull over
and just throw him out here.

87
00:07:11,811 --> 00:07:12,989
OK.

88
00:07:13,060 --> 00:07:16,541
Riley, you're not missing that little
windowless cubicle we found you in?

89
00:07:16,612 --> 00:07:18,652
No, no. Absolutely not.

90
00:07:36,037 --> 00:07:38,754
Why are we stopping?
I thought we were looking for a ship.

91
00:07:38,821 --> 00:07:42,683
- I don't see any ship.
- She's out there.

92
00:07:52,549 --> 00:07:55,866
Look... this is a waste of time.

93
00:07:55,942 --> 00:07:58,844
How could a ship wind up way out here?

94
00:07:58,918 --> 00:08:01,918
Well, I'm no expert, but...

95
00:08:01,990 --> 00:08:04,990
it could be that the hydrothermic properties
of this region

96
00:08:05,063 --> 00:08:07,583
produce hurricane-force ice storms

97
00:08:07,654 --> 00:08:11,549
that cause the ocean to freeze
and then melt and then refreeze,

98
00:08:11,623 --> 00:08:16,096
resulting in a semisolid
migrating land mass

99
00:08:16,167 --> 00:08:19,680
that would land a ship right around here.

100
00:09:06,697 --> 00:09:08,421
Hello, beautiful.

101
00:09:16,329 --> 00:09:19,591
Have Viktor
check the fuel in the generators.

102
00:09:20,042 --> 00:09:24,744
Two years ago, if you hadn't shown up,
hadn't believed the treasure was real,

103
00:09:24,810 --> 00:09:27,014
<i>I don't know
if I ever would have found Charlotte.</i>

104
00:09:27,082 --> 00:09:29,765
You would have found it, I have no doubt.

105
00:09:29,834 --> 00:09:34,057
That's why I didn't think it was
as crazy an investment as everyone said.

106
00:09:34,378 --> 00:09:38,405
<i>I'm just relieved that I'm not as crazy
as everyone says. Or said my dad was.</i>

107
00:09:38,827 --> 00:09:42,853
Or my granddad. Or my great-granddad.

108
00:09:43,402 --> 00:09:45,126
OK!

109
00:09:45,195 --> 00:09:47,170
Let's go!

110
00:09:47,915 --> 00:09:51,744
- Let's go find some treasure.
- Yeah, bring us back something.

111
00:10:01,995 --> 00:10:03,140
Urgh.

112
00:10:28,972 --> 00:10:31,111
Oh, God!

113
00:10:33,933 --> 00:10:35,689
You handled that well.

114
00:10:36,717 --> 00:10:39,019
This is it.

115
00:10:39,469 --> 00:10:41,292
It's the cargo hold.

116
00:10:53,102 --> 00:10:55,753
Do you think it's in the barrels?

117
00:11:13,807 --> 00:11:15,367
Gunpowder.

118
00:11:17,039 --> 00:11:18,981
Ooh! Ooh! OK...

119
00:11:24,207 --> 00:11:27,502
Why would the captain
be guarding this barrel?

120
00:11:51,600 --> 00:11:53,510
I found something!

121
00:11:59,824 --> 00:12:01,734
What is it?

122
00:12:18,514 --> 00:12:20,653
Do you guys know what this is?

123
00:12:21,106 --> 00:12:23,310
Is it a billion-dollar pipe?

124
00:12:25,010 --> 00:12:28,327
It's a meerschaum pipe.
Ah, that is beautiful.

125
00:12:28,402 --> 00:12:31,664
Look at the intricacy of the scrollwork
on the stem.

126
00:12:31,730 --> 00:12:35,757
- Is it a million-dollar pipe?
- No, it's a clue.

127
00:12:35,827 --> 00:12:38,477
Let me see that.

128
00:12:39,442 --> 00:12:41,581
No, don't break it!

129
00:12:41,651 --> 00:12:44,172
We are one step closer to the treasure,
gentlemen.

130
00:12:44,243 --> 00:12:46,763
<i>Ben, I thought you said that
the treasure would be on the Charlotte.</i>

131
00:12:46,835 --> 00:12:49,224
<i>No, "The secret lies with Charlotte."</i>

132
00:12:49,299 --> 00:12:51,306
<i>I said it could be here.</i>

133
00:13:07,508 --> 00:13:10,028
It's Templar symbols.

134
00:13:16,244 --> 00:13:18,186
"The legend writ."

135
00:13:18,260 --> 00:13:20,300
"The stain effected."

136
00:13:20,372 --> 00:13:23,340
"The key in Silence undetected."

137
00:13:23,893 --> 00:13:26,763
"Fifty-five in iron pen."

138
00:13:27,796 --> 00:13:30,098
"Mr. Matlack can't offend."

139
00:13:33,557 --> 00:13:35,662
It's a riddle.

140
00:13:38,677 --> 00:13:40,336
I need to think.

141
00:13:43,702 --> 00:13:45,644
"The legend writ."

142
00:13:45,718 --> 00:13:47,627
"The stain effected."

143
00:13:48,470 --> 00:13:50,379
What legend?

144
00:13:51,350 --> 00:13:55,506
There's the legend of the Templar treasure,
and the stain effects the legend.

145
00:13:55,574 --> 00:13:57,549
How?

146
00:13:57,622 --> 00:13:59,956
"The key in Silence undetected."

147
00:14:00,918 --> 00:14:02,828
Wait.

148
00:14:03,703 --> 00:14:07,565
The legend and the key...
Now there's something.

149
00:14:07,639 --> 00:14:09,046
A map.

150
00:14:09,111 --> 00:14:11,794
Maps have legends, maps have keys.

151
00:14:11,863 --> 00:14:13,968
It's a map, an invisible map.
So now...

152
00:14:14,039 --> 00:14:17,584
Wait a minute. What do you mean,
"invisible" - "an invisible map"?

153
00:14:17,655 --> 00:14:21,779
"The stain effected"
could refer to a dye or a reagent

154
00:14:21,848 --> 00:14:24,303
used to bring about a certain result.

155
00:14:24,376 --> 00:14:27,125
Combined with
"The key in Silence undetected,"

156
00:14:27,192 --> 00:14:31,981
the implication is that the effect is to make
what was undetectable detectable.

157
00:14:32,696 --> 00:14:36,722
Unless...
"The key in Silence" could be...

158
00:14:36,792 --> 00:14:39,214
Prison.

159
00:14:39,993 --> 00:14:41,651
Albuquerque.

160
00:14:41,720 --> 00:14:44,208
See, I can do it too.
Snorkel.

161
00:14:44,281 --> 00:14:46,931
That's where the map is.
Like he said, "Fifty-five in iron pen."

162
00:14:47,001 --> 00:14:48,408
"Iron pen" is a prison.

163
00:14:48,473 --> 00:14:53,688
Or it could be, since the primary writing
medium of the time was iron gall ink,

164
00:14:53,753 --> 00:14:56,567
the "pen" is... just a pen.

165
00:14:56,633 --> 00:15:00,888
But then why not say a pen?
Why... why say "iron pen"?

166
00:15:01,689 --> 00:15:03,664
'Cause it's a prison.

167
00:15:03,738 --> 00:15:07,699
Wait a minute. "Iron pen" - the "iron"
does not describe the ink in the pen,

168
00:15:08,538 --> 00:15:11,255
<i>it describes what was penned.</i>

169
00:15:11,322 --> 00:15:14,453
It was "iron" -
it was firm, it was mineral...

170
00:15:14,521 --> 00:15:16,115
No, no, no, that's stupid.

171
00:15:16,185 --> 00:15:21,423
It was... It was firm,
it was adamant, it was resolved.

172
00:15:23,130 --> 00:15:25,040
It was resolved.

173
00:15:25,786 --> 00:15:27,695
"Mr. Matlack can't offend."

174
00:15:27,770 --> 00:15:31,283
Timothy Matlack was the official scribe
of the Continental Congress.

175
00:15:31,354 --> 00:15:35,511
Calligrapher, not writer. And to make sure
he could not offend the map,

176
00:15:35,578 --> 00:15:39,223
it was put on the back of a resolution
that he transcribed,

177
00:15:39,291 --> 00:15:43,066
a resolution that 55 men signed.

178
00:15:45,691 --> 00:15:48,440
The Declaration of Independence.

179
00:15:50,524 --> 00:15:51,985
Oh!

180
00:15:54,812 --> 00:15:59,067
Come on, there's no invisible map on the
back of the Declaration of Independence.

181
00:15:59,131 --> 00:16:01,520
That's clever, really.
A document of that importance

182
00:16:01,596 --> 00:16:03,735
would ensure the map's survival.

183
00:16:03,804 --> 00:16:06,488
And you said there were several Masons
signed it, yeah?

184
00:16:06,556 --> 00:16:09,687
Yeah. Nine, for sure.

185
00:16:11,004 --> 00:16:14,353
We'll have to arrange a way to examine it.

186
00:16:14,429 --> 00:16:17,528
This is one of the most important
documents in history.

187
00:16:17,597 --> 00:16:21,787
They're not just gonna let us waltz in there
and run chemical tests on it.

188
00:16:21,853 --> 00:16:24,308
- Then what do you propose we do?
- I don't know!

189
00:16:27,997 --> 00:16:30,070
We could borrow it.

190
00:16:31,006 --> 00:16:32,915
Steal it?

191
00:16:34,269 --> 00:16:37,084
- I don't think so.
- Ben...

192
00:16:37,149 --> 00:16:40,466
the treasure of the Knights Templar
is the treasure of all treasures.

193
00:16:40,542 --> 00:16:43,127
Oh, I didn't know that.
Really?

194
00:16:43,934 --> 00:16:48,124
Look, Ben... I understand your bitterness.
I really do.

195
00:16:48,478 --> 00:16:50,486
You've spent your entire life
searching for this treasure,

196
00:16:50,558 --> 00:16:52,664
only to have
the respected historical community

197
00:16:52,734 --> 00:16:56,411
treat you and your family
with mockery and contempt.

198
00:16:56,478 --> 00:16:58,900
You should be able to rub this treasure
in their arrogant faces,

199
00:16:58,974 --> 00:17:01,560
and I want you to have
the chance to do that.

200
00:17:02,527 --> 00:17:03,989
How?

201
00:17:04,383 --> 00:17:07,034
We all have our areas of expertise.

202
00:17:08,127 --> 00:17:11,476
You don't think mine are limited
to writing checks, do you?

203
00:17:11,551 --> 00:17:13,722
In another life...

204
00:17:14,527 --> 00:17:19,994
I arranged a number of operations of...
questionable legality.

205
00:17:22,495 --> 00:17:24,764
I'd take his word for it, if I were you.

206
00:17:26,624 --> 00:17:30,715
So don't worry.
I'll make all the arrangements.

207
00:17:32,320 --> 00:17:33,367
No.

208
00:17:38,816 --> 00:17:41,434
I'd really need your help here.

209
00:17:41,504 --> 00:17:46,839
Ian... I'm not gonna let you steal
the Declaration of Independence.

210
00:17:46,912 --> 00:17:49,018
OK.

211
00:17:49,088 --> 00:17:52,285
From this point on
all you're going to be is a hindrance.

212
00:17:55,009 --> 00:17:55,772
Hey!

213
00:17:55,841 --> 00:17:59,616
What are you gonna do?
Are you gonna shoot me, Shaw?

214
00:18:00,193 --> 00:18:02,876
Well, you can't shoot me.
There's more to the riddle.

215
00:18:02,945 --> 00:18:06,077
Information you don't have. I do.

216
00:18:06,146 --> 00:18:09,081
I'm the only one who can figure it out,
and you know that.

217
00:18:09,154 --> 00:18:11,390
He's bluffing.

218
00:18:11,457 --> 00:18:14,010
We played poker together, Ian.
You know I can't bluff.

219
00:18:14,082 --> 00:18:16,384
Tell me what I need to know, Ben,

220
00:18:16,450 --> 00:18:18,622
or I'll shoot your friend.

221
00:18:18,690 --> 00:18:20,064
Hey!

222
00:18:20,130 --> 00:18:22,367
Quiet, Riley!
Your job's finished here.

223
00:18:26,882 --> 00:18:30,908
Look where you're standing.
All that gunpowder.

224
00:18:30,978 --> 00:18:34,656
You shoot me,
I drop this, we all go up.

225
00:18:36,003 --> 00:18:37,312
Ben...

226
00:18:38,531 --> 00:18:41,531
What happens when the flare burns down?

227
00:18:43,043 --> 00:18:45,596
Tell me what I need to know, Ben.

228
00:18:47,491 --> 00:18:49,051
You need to know...

229
00:18:49,123 --> 00:18:51,011
if Shaw can catch.

230
00:18:56,644 --> 00:18:58,237
Nice try, though.

231
00:19:09,157 --> 00:19:11,066
Get out, Shaw!

232
00:19:19,365 --> 00:19:20,926
Fool!

233
00:19:25,125 --> 00:19:26,882
Riley, get over here!

234
00:19:32,069 --> 00:19:34,524
- What is this?
- Smuggler's hold. Get in!

235
00:19:39,878 --> 00:19:41,220
Move! Get out of here!

236
00:19:41,286 --> 00:19:42,879
- What?
- Move! Get out!

237
00:19:44,006 --> 00:19:45,916
Follow me.

238
00:19:49,414 --> 00:19:51,170
Let's go, let's go!
She's gonna blow!

239
00:19:57,959 --> 00:20:00,031
Get down.

240
00:20:29,736 --> 00:20:33,151
OK, let's go.
Before someone sees the smoke.

241
00:21:02,601 --> 00:21:05,503
There's an Inuit village
about nine miles east of here.

242
00:21:05,578 --> 00:21:09,440
- It's popular with bush pilots.
- All right.

243
00:21:14,186 --> 00:21:17,666
- Then what are we gonna do?
- Start making our way back home.

244
00:21:17,738 --> 00:21:21,929
No, I meant about Ian. He's gonna steal
the Declaration of Independence, Ben.

245
00:21:23,114 --> 00:21:24,740
We stop him.

